{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3413b5ed-2f73-4669-b000-c09fb9037a34",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Simulate a CBC background"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f259f2de-d291-473b-bf3e-c8921ede51a2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This notebook is meant as a tutorial on how to use the `simulator` module within `pygwb` to simulate individual compact binary coalescences (CBC). More information about the `simulator` can be found on the documentation page [here](./_build/html/api/pygwb.simulator.html).\n",
    "\n",
    "We start by importing some packages needed for the execution of the tutorial:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "6ff2b011-3a79-42a2-9028-32e3ae2972bc",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import bilby\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import astropy.units as u\n",
    "from pygwb.detector import Interferometer\n",
    "from pygwb.network import Network\n",
    "from pygwb.simulator import Simulator\n",
    "%matplotlib inline"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b0c5c9e6-1e51-48d2-82a1-6806a0837508",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "*Note: make sure to run this notebook within an environment that has all the above packages installed.*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c676c217-0bfd-45c8-9fad-62d58d228eb0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Injection of CBCs"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d77da657-0461-4769-b5d4-428790f8cbfd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For this tutorial, we consider the injection of individual CBC using the `simulator` module and `bilby`. The various steps to get to the simulated data are outlined below."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "90780604-9295-403f-ad40-e70d23b59da7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Simulation parameters"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d6db9fa5-47e6-4afa-940c-038c3ff3d82d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We start by specifying the parameters that will serve as input to the simulator. Concretely, we specify the duration of each simulated segment, the number of segments, and the sampling frequency."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "bfc41c46-68b6-4c11-b180-6333f8b611ae",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "duration = 64 # duration of each segment of data (s)\n",
    "N_segs = 5  # number of data segments to generate\n",
    "sampling_frequency = 1024 # Hz"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0d1d9061-8a2b-4ed1-b01f-7f8e1c65f0b5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Initialize empty interferometers and set a noise PSD to use in the simulation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1d5b4c00-bd1a-4661-8af3-6c1710aa2374",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "By relying on the `detector` module, we instantiate various detectors below. For this tutorial, we decide to use the LIGO Hanford (H1) and LIGO Livingston (L1) detectors as an example. However, note that the data can be simulated for an arbitrary amount of detectors. One would simply add more detectors to the *ifo_list* below."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "8a6b20e8-ddec-49da-bb21-c1dcb4c5eaed",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ifo_H1 = Interferometer.get_empty_interferometer('H1')\n",
    "ifo_L1 = Interferometer.get_empty_interferometer('L1')\n",
    "\n",
    "ifo_list = [ifo_H1, ifo_L1]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "68672077-cb5a-4107-82f3-b0f0ba84099b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The above detectors are `Interferometer` objects, but are based on `bilby` detectors, which have default noise power spectral densities (PSDs) saved in them, in the `power_spectral_density` attribute of the `bilby` detector. Below, we load in this noise PSD and make sure the duration and sampling frequency of the detector is set to the desired value of these parameters chosen at the start of the notebook."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "2361e31b-9252-4a0a-b2dd-048b31547723",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "for ifo in ifo_list:\n",
    "    ifo.duration = duration\n",
    "    ifo.sampling_frequency = sampling_frequency\n",
    "    ifo.power_spectral_density = bilby.gw.detector.PowerSpectralDensity(ifo.frequency_array, np.nan_to_num(ifo.power_spectral_density_array, posinf=1.e-41))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1b2bf311-db37-4894-bc7e-75948f990ec9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To illustrate the last few steps, we plot the PSD for the H1 detector."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "2ffcc18d-4b82-4cf5-b0d4-3c0dcf41df6d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7fcae8079d60>]"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 5,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.loglog(ifo_H1.power_spectral_density.psd_array)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ea12d3ac-d25b-4b40-9683-de659ae8ffc1",
   "metadata": {
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "### Initialize a network with the interferometer list"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "765ade09-98d8-43fd-8c65-ae204a1a9cfb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Although the `simulator` module can be called directly, it is useful to rely on the `network` module and call the dedicated methods of that module (which calls the `simulator` behind the screens). We therefore create a network of detectors, by calling:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "8dd03f42-c440-40a8-878a-09ddc779884a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "net_HL = Network('HL', ifo_list)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e3645c41-5f27-4143-90ca-9127a2d0dba2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Describing the CBC population used for the simulation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6bbe32f6-0fd9-4a23-bbb7-7786f7310f71",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Before being able to simulate CBCs, we need to specify which population the CBC events are drawn from. This is done by using `bilby` priors. This allows the user to specify the distributions of the various parameters that come into play in CBC waveforms. A few examples are given below."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "8a116d29-3a66-4e25-8a23-765c55a45dda",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "05:39 bilby INFO    : Using aligned spin prior\n",
      "05:39 bilby INFO    : No prior given, using default BBH priors in /home/kevin.turbang/.conda/envs/pygwb_maintenance/lib/python3.9/site-packages/bilby/gw/prior_files/aligned_spins_bbh.prior.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "priors = bilby.gw.prior.BBHPriorDict(aligned_spin=True)\n",
    "priors['chirp_mass'] = bilby.core.prior.Uniform(2, 30, name=\"chirp_mass\")\n",
    "priors['mass_ratio'] = 1.0\n",
    "priors['chi_1'] = 0\n",
    "priors['chi_2'] = 0\n",
    "priors['luminosity_distance'] = bilby.core.prior.PowerLaw(alpha=2, name='luminosity_distance', \n",
    "                                                          minimum=10, maximum=100, \n",
    "                                                          unit='Mpc')\n",
    "priors[\"geocent_time\"] = bilby.core.prior.Uniform(0, duration*N_segs, name=\"geocent_time\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# create 20 injections\n",
    "injections = priors.sample(20)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3092803a-eb06-49d3-8b99-843708661c45",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The output of the cell above is a dictionary containing the injections, which wills erve as input for the `simulator`. It can be very useful to save these injections to file, for later use. This is done by executing the following lines of code:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "74bb586f-203e-4788-9949-3e17d9a670c2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import json\n",
    "\n",
    "with open(\"injections.json\", \"w\") as file:\n",
    "    json.dump(\n",
    "        injections, file, indent=2, cls=bilby.core.result.BilbyJsonEncoder\n",
    "    )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6f126616-9a9c-4fa9-99a6-2e39f64050f7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Simulate the CBCs and Gaussian noise"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "579fd08f-e12f-4dd2-aed7-b22faa635c56",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We are now ready to simulate the data, consisting of a CBCs and Gaussian noise, colored by the noise PSD saved in each of the detectors. We rely on the `network` module to simulate the data by calling the `set_interferometer_data_from_simulator` method (which uses the `simulator` module)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "28510146-b212-4211-b95d-32c099f837e5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "/home/kevin.turbang/.conda/envs/pygwb_maintenance/lib/python3.9/site-packages/pygwb/network.py:220: UserWarning: User did not specify a start time. Setting start time to zero.\n",
      "  warnings.warn(\n",
      "100%|██████████| 20/20 [00:03<00:00,  5.58it/s]\n",
      "100%|██████████| 20/20 [00:03<00:00,  6.62it/s]\n",
      "2023-05-23 05:39:43.635 | INFO     | pygwb.simulator:generate_data:272 - Adding data to channel H1:SIM-STOCH_INJ\n",
      "2023-05-23 05:39:43.683 | INFO     | pygwb.simulator:generate_data:272 - Adding data to channel L1:SIM-STOCH_INJ\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import logging\n",
    "logging.getLogger(\"bilby\").setLevel(logging.WARNING)\n",
    "\n",
    "net_HL.set_interferometer_data_from_simulator(N_segs, CBC_dict=injections, sampling_frequency = sampling_frequency)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f3ee76f6-a96d-44d5-a635-9416f91022de",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We show the simulated data below, illustrating that Gaussian noise and CBC injections were simulated correctly."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "a37b48f6-0c08-4f98-bac6-d6bda9b488d2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Plot size 1200x400 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 10,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {

       "<Plot size 1200x400 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "net_HL.interferometers[0].strain_data.to_gwpy_timeseries().whiten().plot()"
   ]
  }
